Content Arsenal: Templates That Convert
The Hacker News Post Formula
	•	Title: 'Show HN: [Product] – [One-line value prop with technical specificity]'
	•	First comment (by you, as maker): Origin story (what pain you felt), technical architecture choice (why deterministic > probabilistic), a live demo link, and 'happy to answer any questions.'
	•	Never say 'we' if you're solo. Say 'I built.' Authenticity wins on HN.
The Twitter/X Thread Formula
	•	Tweet 1: Provocative claim or question. 'Your AI agent guardrails are security theater. Here's why.'
	•	Tweets 2-5: Evidence, data, or code screenshots supporting the claim.
	•	Tweet 6: The solution (SupraWall), with a code example or GIF.
	•	Tweet 7: CTA. 'It's open source. Star it, try it, break it. [link]'
The Reddit Post Formula
	•	Title: Problem-first, not product-first. 'How we solved X' > 'Announcing Y.'
	•	Body: 80% educational content, 15% your experience, 5% repo link.
	•	Always engage with every comment. Reddit rewards engagement.

The 5 Make-or-Break Factors
1. The Product Must Work on Day 1
This is the single most important factor and the one that makes or breaks the entire plan. Every channel collapses if someone pip installs your package and it doesn't work, throws errors, or takes more than 60 seconds to see results. Paperclip shipped a working product on day 1. Every successful OSS launch in the research did the same. No amount of marketing fixes a broken install experience.
2. The Narrative Must Be Provocative and Clear
'Agent runtime firewall' is technically accurate but not viral. 'Your agents don't need better guardrails — they need a firewall' is. Every piece of content must lead with the contrarian take: guardrails are probabilistic and insufficient for production. SupraWall is deterministic and complete. This is the same pattern Paperclip used: 'your agents don't need better prompts, they need an org chart.'
3. You Must Stack Distribution Events
Isolated posts get isolated results. The magic happens when you stack: a blog post + a Twitter thread + a Reddit post + a Discord share all hit on the same day. This creates the illusion of 'everyone is talking about this,' which triggers organic amplification. GitHub's Trending algorithm specifically rewards spikes in stars over 24-48 hour windows.
4. Respond to Everything Within 1 Hour
Every GitHub issue, every Reddit comment, every Twitter reply, every Discord question. Speed of response is the strongest signal that a project is alive and maintained. It also triggers platform algorithms — posts with active comment threads rank higher on every platform.
5. Ship Updates Every Week
Releases are content. Every v0.x.0 release gives you a reason to post again: 'New in SupraWall v0.2: Docker support, audit logs, and 3x faster policy evaluation.' This is the NeMo Guardrails playbook — their release notes are their marketing engine.

